# Aryan and the Little Golden Loaf

Aryan was tired.

Not the regular kind of tired — the deep, bone-weary kind that comes from too many late-night deploys, too many Slack pings, and one too many meetings that "could've been an email." His apartment was quiet, his coffee was cold, and his houseplant was judging him. ☕🪴

"I need something in my life," he mumbled to the ceiling. "Something soft. Something that doesn't send calendar invites."

That Saturday, he found himself standing in front of a small animal shelter, blinking against the morning sun. He didn't really plan on going in. His feet just sort of… took him there.

Inside, the volunteer smiled. "Looking for anyone in particular?"

"I don't know," Aryan said honestly. "Something that matches my energy."

She laughed and led him to a sunny corner — and there, curled into a perfect round loaf on a fleece blanket, was a **golden British Shorthair**. Plush. Round. The color of toasted honey. Two huge copper eyes blinked up at him, slow and unbothered, as if to say: *Oh. It's you. Took you long enough.* 🍞✨

"His name is Biscuit," the volunteer said. "He's… not very energetic."

"Perfect," Aryan whispered.

Biscuit did not stand up. Biscuit did not greet him. Biscuit yawned — a tiny pink triangle of a yawn — and tucked his paw further under his chin. Aryan was, immediately and irreversibly, in love. 💛

---

That night, Biscuit explored the apartment with the urgency of a retired professor on vacation. He sniffed one corner. Considered the couch. Decided the couch was acceptable. Then he climbed — slowly, dramatically — into Aryan's lap and became, once again, a loaf.

Aryan looked down at the warm golden weight on his legs. Biscuit's purr was deep and steady, like a tiny idling engine. The cold coffee was forgotten. The Slack notifications were forgotten. Even the judgmental houseplant seemed to soften. 🌿

"Hi, Biscuit," Aryan whispered, scratching behind one velvety ear.

Biscuit blinked slowly. *Hi, human. We nap now.*

And so they did.

For the first time in a long time, Aryan wasn't tired in the sad way. He was tired in the good way — the kind of tired you earn from a full heart and a warm cat and absolutely nowhere else to be. 😺💤

The end.
